{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}} {{Infobox writer | name = Baldev Singh | image = Punjabi Poet Baldev Singh Sadaknama.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> {{Birth year and age|1942}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = Novelist, story writer | language = | nationality = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = M.A., B.Ed. | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''Dhahwan Dilli De Kingre'', ''Sarhaknama'', ''[[Laal Batti]]'' | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | awards = [[List of Sahitya Akademi Award winners for Punjabi|Sahitya Akademi Award]] (2011) | signature = | signature_alt = | module = | website = | portaldisp = | known for = Sarknamma }}
'''Baldev Singh''' (born 1942, also known as '''Baldev Singh Sadaknaama''') is a [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] novelist and story writer<ref name="hp">{{cite web|url=http://www.hunpanjabi.net/company/member-details.aspx?mc=25 |title=ਬਲਦੇਵ ਸਿੰਘ |accessdate=17 December 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219021032/http://www.hunpanjabi.net/company/member-details.aspx?mc=25 |archivedate=19 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> of [[Punjab, India]].<ref name="tribune2003">{{cite news |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030525/spectrum/book5.htm |title=Punjabi literature Focusing on the problems of Punjab peasantry |last=Singh |first=Jaspal |date=25 May 2003 |work=''[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]'' |accessdate=18 December 2013 |location=Chandigarh, India}}</ref> He received the [[List of Sahitya Akademi Award winners for Punjabi|Sahitya Akademi Award]] 2011 for his novel ''Dhahwan Dilli De Kingre''.<ref name="pt">{{cite web |url=http://punjabitribuneonline.com/category/%E0%A8%A6%E0%A8%B8%E0%A8%A4%E0%A8%95/page/6/ |title=ਮਾਂ-ਬੋਲੀ ਪੰਜਾਬੀ ਦੇ ਸੁੱਚੇ ਮੋਤੀ |accessdate= 17 December 2013}}</ref><ref name="hp"/> As of 2012, he has written 55 novels and various short stories and plays.<ref name=truth/>
==Early life== Baldev Singh was born in the village Chand Nawaan, in the [[Moga, Punjab]] district. He started his career as a teacher in the [[Muktsar]] area and spent some time in Himachal Pradesh as a teacher as well. Later he moved to [[Calcutta]] and worked as a truck cleaner, taxi driver and truck operator.
==Career== Singh is known for his novels ''Sadaknaama'' and ''Laal Batti''. His novel ''Sadaknaama'' was a road narrative of truck drivers from Punjab. It started as a column in [[Amrita Pritam]]'s magazine ''Nagmani'' and was later published as a [[three-volume novel]]. The stories in the novel were based on Singh's real experiences. He himself was a truck driver for 10 years, while working as a teacher. The book became very popular in Punjabi literature and "Sadaknaama" became part of his name for his fans.<ref name=truth>{{cite web | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2012/20120122/spectrum/book7.htm | title=The Truth Behind The Fiction | publisher=''[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]'' | date=22 January 2012 | accessdate=18 December 2013 | author=Singh, Nonika}}</ref>
His novel ''Laal Batti'' dealt with the [[red-light area]] of Kolkatta, for which he studied his subject for over a decade. It was also adapted into play by Manch Rang Manch, and directed by [[Kewal Dhaliwal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_11-3-2005_pg7_22 |title=Theatre lovers flock to Panj Pani festival on 4th day |publisher=[[Daily Times (Pakistan)|''Daily Times'' (Pakistan)]] |place=Lahore |date=11 March 2005 |accessdate=18 December 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219012522/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_11-3-2005_pg7_22 |archivedate=19 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> His novel ''Annadaata'' was about plights of farmers in Punjab and is also part of the [[Punjabi literature]] curriculum in the [[Guru Nanak Dev University]] and [[Punjabi University]]. He plans to write sequels to both these books. His play ''Mitti Rudan Kare'' also remains popular.<ref name=truth/>
His latest work ''Dhahwan Dilli De Kingre'' was about the legendary rebel [[Dulla Bhatti]]. The novel won him a Sahitya Akademi Award for Punjabi in 2011.<ref name=truth/>
