'''GNOME Dictionary''', also called '''gnome-dictionary''', is a [[DICT client]] written in [[C (programming language)|C]] by Emmanuele Bassi and others. It is part of the [[free software]] [[GNOME]] desktop suite. It allows users to look up words in various dictionary sources.

gnome-dictionary was at first an independent [[DICT]] protocol client called '''gdict''', created by Bradford Hovinen, Spiros Papadimitriou and Mike Hughes;<ref>
[https://git.gnome.org/browse/gnome-dictionary/log/ gdict ChangeLog]</ref> it was included inside the gnome-utils meta-package during the 1.x release cycle.  As a companion to the original application was also added an [[applet]] for [[gnome-panel]].

After the 2.0 release of GNOME, due to lack of direct maintainership, the code base of gdict passed the point of being maintainable.  In October 2005, the current maintainer of gnome-dictionary Emmanuele Bassi decided to [[Rewrite (programming)|rewrite]] the application and applet from scratch, removing the old (and mostly deprecated) code.<ref>[http://mail.gnome.org/archives/gnome-utils-list/2005-October/msg00004.html Email on the gnome-utils mailing list about the re-design]</ref>

The new gnome-dictionary was added to GNOME during the 2.13 development cycle and became part of the 2.14 GNOME release.  It supports multiple dictionary sources, printing the definitions found and saving them to a text file, and has a simpler user interface. The logic of the application and the applet has been moved inside its own [[Library (computer science)|shared library]] called libgdict which can be used by third party applications. As of July 2006 the development version of gnome-dictionary became feature equivalent to the pre-2.14 release,<ref>[http://log.emmanuelebassi.net/archives/2006/07/rainbows-and-pots-of-gold/ Announce on Emmanuele Bassi's blog about the speller widget]</ref> with the addition of the list of similar words found (also known as ''speller'').

