{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}} {{refimprove|date= May 2012}} {{Infobox person |name=Girijashankar Bhagwanji Badheka |image=Gijubhai Badheka.jpg |birth_date = 15 November 1885 |death_date = {{death-date and age|23 June 1939|15 November 1885}} |caption= Gijubhai Badheka |birth_place=Chittal, [[Saurashtra (region)]], India |death_place=[[Bhavnagar]], [[Gujarat]], India |known_for=Education, Reforms, Children's Education, Dakshinamurti. Also known as '''Moochali Maa''' }} '''Gijubhai Badheka''' (15 November 1885 – 23 June 1939) born in Chittal, was an [[Education#Theory|educator]] who helped to introduce [[Montessori education]] methods to India.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gijubhai Badheka: An inspiring teacher though Montessori |url=http://ngopost.org/story/gijubhai-badheka-inspiring-teacher-though-montessori |work=NGOpost.org |publisher=NGOpost.org |accessdate=30 March 2012 |author=Goli |format=Web page |date=30 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411125406/http://ngopost.org/story/gijubhai-badheka-inspiring-teacher-though-montessori |archivedate=11 April 2012 |df= }}</ref> He is referred to as "Moochhali Maa" ("mother with whiskers"). Badheka was a [[List of High Courts of India|high court]] lawyer,however, following the birth of his son in 1923, he developed an interest in childhood development and education. In 1920, Badheka founded the "Bal Mandir" [[Kindergarten#India|pre-primary]] school.<ref name=Learning>{{cite web |title=Gijubhai on Education |url=http://www.learningnet-india.org/publications/revive/vol6/v6-2-8.php |work=Learning Network Initiative |publisher=The Learning Network |accessdate=30 March 2012 |author=Mamata Pandya |format=Web page |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927215039/http://www.learningnet-india.org/publications/revive/vol6/v6-2-8.php |archivedate=27 September 2013 |df= }}</ref> Badheka published a number of works in the field of education including ''Divaswapna'' ("Daydreams").<ref name=Learning />
==Life== Badheka was born in the [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] region of western India. His given (first) name was "Girijashankar". Badheka grew up in [[Bhavnagar]], a city in the western Indian state of [[Gujarat]]. In 1907, he moved to East Africa and later, [[Bombay]] for work. Badheka died on 23 June 1939 in Bhavnagar, India. {{citation needed|date= May 2012}}
==Contribution to education== In 1920, Badheka founded the Bal Mandir kindergarten. Later, [[Nanabhai Bhatt (Lokbharti)|Nanabhai Bhatt]], Harbhai Trivedi and Badheka built the "Shree Dakshinamurti Gijubhai Vinay Mandir" school in Bhavnagar.<ref>{{cite web |title=Welcome to Shree Dakshinamurti Vinay Mandir |url=http://www.shreedakshinamurtivinaymandir.org/index.aspx |work=shreedakshinamurtivinaymandir.org |publisher=Shree Dakshinamurti Gijubhai Mandir |accessdate=30 March 2012 |format=Web page |year=2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324221911/http://www.shreedakshinamurtivinaymandir.org/index.aspx |archivedate=24 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>
==Published works== Badheka published close to 200 works including storybooks.<ref name=Learning/> His topics include children, education, travel and humour. However, his focus was books for children, parents and educators.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}
