'''Jostein Nerbøvik''' (10 July 1938 – 18 March 2004) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[historian]].
He was born in [[Volda]], and took his [[cand.philol.]] degree at the [[University of Oslo]]. He first worked at [[Telemark University College]], then at [[Volda University College]]. He was appointed professor there in 1993, having taken the [[dr.philos.]] degree<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aasentunet.no/default.asp?menu=96&id=532|title=Jostein Nerbøvik er død|last=Grepstad|first=Ottar|authorlink=Ottar Grepstad|date=18 March 2004|publisher=Ivar Aasen Centre|accessdate=29 January 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716074822/http://www.aasentunet.no/default.asp?menu=96&id=532|archivedate=16 July 2011|df=}}</ref> and the [[University of Trondheim]] with the thesis ''Bygdefolkets krisehjelp 1925–35''. The opponents at the dispute were [[Tore Pryser]] and [[Hans Fredrik Dahl]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Pryser|first=Tore|authorlink=Tore Pryser|title=Varulven og andre agenthistorier. Svik og gråsoner under 2. verdenskrig|year=2011|publisher=Spartacus|location=Oslo|language=Norwegian|isbn=978-82-430-0604-1|page=63}}</ref> Nerbøvik was also instrumental in establishing the [[Ivar Aasen Centre]].<ref name=aft>{{cite news|title=Et dannet menneske fra Volda|last=Skre|first=Arnhild|authorlink=Arnhild Skre|date=26 March 2004|work=[[Aftenposten]]}}</ref>
In 1973 Nerbøvik published his most well-known book; the general overview ''Norsk historie 1870–1905''.<ref name=aft/> It was later remade into ''Norsk historie 1860–1914. Eit bondesamfunn i oppbrot'', published in 1999 as volume three of ''[[Norsk historie (Samlaget)|Samlagets norske historie]]'', a series on Norwegian history spanning the years 800 to 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samlaget.no/Utdanning/HU/Boeker/Historie-og-kulturvitskap/Historie/Norsk-historie-1860-1914.aspx|title=Norsk historie 1860-1914. Eit bondesamfunn i oppbrot|publisher=Det Norske Samlaget|language=Norwegian|accessdate=29 January 2009}}</ref> As the title indicates, Nerbøvik stressed the activity of the Norwegian rural populace in the [[democratization]] process in the second half of the nineteenth century.<ref name=aft/>
He died in March 2004 at [[Rikshospitalet]], having gone through a lengthy struggle with cancer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jostein Nerbøvik 1938-2004|last=Nore|first=Aslak|authorlink=Aslak Nore|date=20 March 2004|work=[[Klassekampen]]}}</ref>
