{{Use Indian English|date=August 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | image = Madampu Kunjukuttan IMG 9615.jpg | name = Madampu Sankaran Namboothiri | pseudonym = Madampu Kunjukuttan | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1941|06|23}} | birth_place = [[Kiralur]], [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]], India | occupation = [[Novelist]], [[Short story writer]], [[Screenplay writer]], [[Priest]], [[Teacher]], [[Actor]] | nationality = Indian | genre = [[Novel]], [[Short story]] | subject = Social aspects | spouse = Savithri Antharjanam (late) | awards = Best [[Screenwriter|screenplay writer]], [[Kerala Sahitya Academy Award]] }}
'''Madampu Sankaran Namboothiri''', popularly known as '''Madampu Kunjukuttan''', is a [[Malayalam]] author and a [[screenplay writer]].<ref>http://www.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/malayalamContentView.do?contentId=15580175&tabId=8&BV_ID=@@@</ref> He is one of the most prolific and versatile writers in modern Malayalam literature. His novels, short stories and screenplays speaks more about the [[Kerala]] society. He has won the [[National Film Award for Best Screenplay]] in the year 2000 for the Malayalam film ''Karunam'', directed by [[Jayaraj]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2000/jul/06nat.htm |title=Movies: National Awards announced!|publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |accessdate=2009-07-02}}</ref> In 2003, he won the Ashdod International Film Award for Best Screenplay for the film ''[[Parinamam]] (The Change)'' directed by [[P.Venu]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/231480/Madampu-Kunjukuttan |title=Madampu Kunjukuttan |publisher=NYTimes |accessdate=2014-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asianetnews.tv/janavidhi2014/article/9078_Election2014:-Matambu-Kunjukuttan |title=Madampu Kunjukuttan on election fever |publisher=Asianetnews |accessdate=2014-08-20}}</ref> He received [[Sanjayan]] Award in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dcbooks.com/sanjayan-award-to-madampu-kunjukuttan.html|title=സഞ്ജയന്‍ പുരസ്‌കാരം മാടമ്പ് കുഞ്ഞുകുട്ടന്|accessdate=2 January 2015|publisher=[[DC Books]]}}</ref>
==Background and personal life== He was born in [[Kiralur]] village [[Thrissur District]] on 23 June 1941. He studied Sanskrit, Hasthyaayurvedam (treatment of elephants), worked as teacher for Sanskrit at [[Kodungalloor]] and was also a priest in a nearby temple. Madampu also worked for Ākāsha Vāṇī ([[All India Radio]]). He was married to late Savithri Antharjanam and he has two daughters, Jaseena Madampu and Haseena Madampu.
